                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d607">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense(M)Peru/601: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-03-29T21:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 29, 1943—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>379. For Thompson from Rosenthal, BEW. Your 379, March 17. We agree to necessity
                    of obtaining assurance against an increase in export taxes and approve the
                    policy you are following.</p>
                <p>We prefer following modification of your suggested wording of Article III: “For
                    the term of this agreement the Government of Peru agrees not to cause any
                    increases in present export taxes on strategic metals and minerals. It also
                    agrees not to impose any other taxes, fees or charges which would have the
                    effect of reducing the incentive to strategic mineral production.”</p>
                <p>If you disagree with this change or if it is unacceptable please let us know.
                    [Rosenthal.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
